definitions.example: In case of fire, get out by the nearest exit.

definitions.definition: To come out of a situation; to escape a fate.
definitions.example: Never take life seriously. Nobody gets out alive anyways.

definitions.definition: To be released, especially from hospital or prison.
definitions.example: He's been in prison for six months, but he gets out next week.

definitions.definition: To remove one's money from an investment; to end an investment.
definitions.example: I think copper prices will plummet this fall, so I'm getting out while I can.
We must get the children out first.

definitions.definition: To take (something) from its container or storage place, so as to use or display it.
definitions.example: Get the playing cards out and we'll have a game of snap.

definitions.definition: To leave a vehicle such as a car. (Note: for public transport, get off is more common.)
definitions.example: I'll get out at the end of the road and walk from there.

definitions.definition: To spend free time out of the house.
definitions.example: You work too hard. You should get out more.

definitions.definition: To publish or make available; to disseminate.
definitions.example: The organization has just gotten their newsletter out.
He could hardly get the words out for the tears.

definitions.definition: To remove or eliminate (dirt or stains).
definitions.example: This detergent will get most household stains out.
Get out! I never want to see you in here again!

definitions.definition: Expressing disapproval or disgust, especially after a bad joke.
